    <header>
      <div class="badge">Setup Guide</div>
      <h1>How to Install Google Analytics MCP</h1>
      <p>Connect your Google Analytics data directly to Claude — no coding experience required. Follow these steps one by one.</p>
    </header>

    <div class="content">

      <div class="intro">
        <strong>What you'll end up with:</strong> Claude will be able to read your Google Analytics data and answer questions like "How many users visited our site last week?" or "What are our top traffic sources?" — right inside your chat.
      </div>

      <!-- STEP 1 -->
      <div class="step">
        <div class="step-number">1</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <h2>Open Claude Cowork and start a session</h2>
          <div class="where-label where-claude">🖥 In the Claude desktop app</div>
          <p>Open the <strong>Claude desktop app</strong> on your Mac. In the left sidebar, click <strong>Cowork</strong> to open a Cowork session. You can use an existing project or create a new one — either works.</p>
          <div class="tip"><strong>Tip:</strong> Cowork is the mode that lets Claude work with files and run commands on your computer. You'll need it for the steps below.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <hr>

      <!-- STEP 2 -->
      <div class="step">
        <div class="step-number">2</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <h2>Open the Terminal app on your Mac</h2>
          <div class="where-label where-claude">🖥 On your Mac</div>
          <p>The next few steps require typing commands into the <strong>Terminal</strong> — a text window where you give your computer instructions by typing.</p>
          <p>To open it:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Press <code>Cmd + Space</code> to open Spotlight Search</li>
            <li>Type <strong>Terminal</strong> and press Enter</li>
          </ul>
          <p>A window will appear with a blinking cursor. You'll just be copying and pasting commands — no typing from scratch.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <hr>

      <!-- STEP 3 -->
      <div class="step">
        <div class="step-number">3</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <h2>Install pipx (a tool that installs other tools)</h2>
          <div class="where-label where-terminal">⌨️ In Terminal</div>
          <p>Copy the line below, paste it into Terminal, and press <strong>Enter</strong>:</p>
          <div class="code-block">brew install pipx && pipx ensurepath</div>
          <p>Wait for it to finish — it may take a minute or two. When you see the cursor again, it's done.</p>
          <div class="warning"><strong>⚠️ Getting a "brew: command not found" error?</strong> You need to install Homebrew first. Go to <a href="https://brew.sh" target="_blank">brew.sh</a>, copy the one-line command shown there, paste it in Terminal, and press Enter. Then come back and run the command above.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <hr>

      <!-- STEP 4 -->
      <div class="step">
        <div class="step-number">4</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <h2>Switch on the Google Analytics APIs</h2>
          <div class="where-label where-browser">🌐 In your web browser</div>
          <p>You need to turn on two services in Google Cloud so Claude is allowed to read your Analytics data. You'll need a Google account that has access to your Google Analytics.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Go to <a href="https://console.cloud.google.com" target="_blank">console.cloud.google.com</a> and sign in</li>
            <li>At the top, select an existing project or create a new one (name it anything, e.g. <em>analytics-mcp</em>)</li>
            <li>Open the <a href="https://console.cloud.google.com/apis/library/analyticsadmin.googleapis.com" target="_blank">Google Analytics Admin API</a> page and click <strong>Enable</strong></li>
            <li>Open the <a href="https://console.cloud.google.com/apis/library/analyticsdata.googleapis.com" target="_blank">Google Analytics Data API</a> page and click <strong>Enable</strong></li>
          </ul>
          <div class="tip"><strong>Tip:</strong> Make sure the same project is selected in the top dropdown for both APIs.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <hr>

      <!-- STEP 5 -->
      <div class="step">
        <div class="step-number">5</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <h2>Create a login credential file</h2>
          <div class="where-label where-browser">🌐 In your web browser</div>
          <p>This creates a "key" file that lets Claude log in to Google on your behalf.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Go to <a href="https://console.cloud.google.com/apis/credentials" target="_blank">console.cloud.google.com/apis/credentials</a></li>
            <li>Click <strong>+ Create Credentials → OAuth client ID</strong></li>
            <li>If prompted to set up a consent screen first: choose <strong>External</strong>, fill in your app name (e.g. <em>analytics-mcp</em>) and email, save, then come back</li>
            <li>Set Application type to <strong>Desktop app</strong>, give it any name, click <strong>Create</strong></li>
            <li>Click <strong>Download JSON</strong> in the dialog that appears</li>
            <li>Move the downloaded file to your home folder and rename it <code>analytics-mcp-credentials.json</code></li>
          </ul>
          <div class="tip"><strong>Where is my home folder?</strong> Open Finder → click <strong>Go</strong> in the menu bar → click <strong>Home</strong>. Drag the file there.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <hr>

      <!-- STEP 6 -->
      <div class="step">
        <div class="step-number">6</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <h2>Install the Google Cloud CLI tool</h2>
          <div class="where-label where-browser">🌐 Browser + ⌨️ Terminal</div>
          <p>Download the installer from <a href="https://cloud.google.com/sdk/docs/install" target="_blank">cloud.google.com/sdk/docs/install</a> — choose the <strong>macOS</strong> version. Once downloaded, go to Terminal and run:</p>
          <div class="code-block">cd ~/Downloads/google-cloud-sdk
bash install.sh</div>
          <p>Press <strong>Y</strong> when asked. When it finishes, reload your Terminal settings:</p>
          <div class="code-block">source ~/.zshrc</div>
          <p>Then check it worked:</p>
          <div class="code-block">gcloud --version</div>
          <p>If you see a version number, you're good to go.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <hr>

      <!-- STEP 7 -->
      <div class="step">
        <div class="step-number">7</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <h2>Sign in to Google from Terminal</h2>
          <div class="where-label where-terminal">⌨️ In Terminal</div>
          <p>Run this command. Replace <code class="highlight">YOUR_USERNAME</code> with your Mac username — it's the name shown before the <code>$</code> symbol in Terminal:</p>
          <div class="code-block">gcloud auth application-default login \
  --scopes https://www.googleapis.com/auth/analytics.readonly,https://www.googleapis.com/auth/cloud-platform \
  --client-id-file=/Users/<span class="highlight">YOUR_USERNAME</span>/analytics-mcp-credentials.json</div>
          <p>A browser window will open. Sign in with the Google account that has access to your Analytics and click <strong>Allow</strong>.</p>
          <p>When done, Terminal will print something like:</p>
          <div class="code-block">Credentials saved to file: [/Users/yourname/.config/gcloud/application_default_credentials.json]</div>
          <p><strong>Copy that file path</strong> — you'll need it in the next step.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <hr>

      <!-- STEP 8 -->
      <div class="step">
        <div class="step-number">8</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <h2>Tell Claude how to connect to Google Analytics</h2>
          <div class="where-label where-terminal">⌨️ In Terminal</div>
          <p>Paste this into Terminal. Replace the two <span style="color:#e08000; font-weight:600;">highlighted values</span> with your own:</p>
          <div class="code-block">mkdir -p ~/Library/Application\ Support/Claude && cat > ~/Library/Application\ Support/Claude/claude_desktop_config.json << 'EOF'
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "analytics-mcp": {
      "command": "pipx",
      "args": ["run", "analytics-mcp"],
      "env": {
        "GOOGLE_APPLICATION_CREDENTIALS": "<span class="highlight">/Users/yourname/.config/gcloud/application_default_credentials.json</span>",
        "GOOGLE_PROJECT_ID": "<span class="highlight">your-gcp-project-id</span>"
      }
    }
  }
}
EOF</div>
          <ul>
            <li>Replace the credentials path with the one Terminal printed in Step 7</li>
            <li>Replace <code>your-gcp-project-id</code> with your project ID, visible at the top of <a href="https://console.cloud.google.com" target="_blank">console.cloud.google.com</a></li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
      <hr>

      <!-- STEP 9 -->
      <div class="step">
        <div class="step-number">9</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <h2>Restart Claude and test it</h2>
          <div class="where-label where-claude">🖥 In the Claude desktop app</div>
          <p>Fully quit Claude with <strong>Cmd + Q</strong> and reopen it. A simple window close won't work — it needs a full restart.</p>
          <p>Once it's back open, go to Cowork and type:</p>
          <div class="code-block">What Google Analytics properties do I have access to?</div>
          <p>If everything worked, Claude will list your GA accounts and properties. 🎉</p>
          <div class="tip"><strong>Something not working?</strong> The most common issue is a typo in the credentials file path in Step 8. Check that it exactly matches what Terminal printed in Step 7.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

